{"runId":"openai-gpt-oss-120b-nitro@2026-05-13T22-32-06-039Z","slug":"securing-clawdbot-tailscale","locale":"ja","model":"openai/gpt-oss-120b:nitro","modelPath":"openai-gpt-oss-120b-nitro","createdAt":"2026-05-13T22:32:12.384Z","sourcePath":"src/content/posts/2026-01-26--securing-clawdbot-tailscale/index.mdx","targetPath":"src/content/posts/2026-01-26--securing-clawdbot-tailscale/ja/index.mdx","candidatePath":"reports/i18n/securing-clawdbot-tailscale/ja/openai-gpt-oss-120b-nitro/2026-05-13T22-32-06-039Z/candidate.mdx","sourceHash":"774feafac3dd3c408584db2b169a365e3f58a8b6a6d0541778aad55f122f5285","outputHash":"47f9e45aace38f07b3a03ba501905949a1058b75a9dca0619e5012ec30913ad7","reasoningEffort":"low","temperature":0.3,"maxTokens":16000,"timeoutMs":200000,"articleSummary":"The articlewarns that exposing OpenClaw’s gateway, node controls, or SSH to the public internet gives attackers direct shell access, and it presents a “keep‑it‑local‑by‑default” security model. It explains three attack surfaces (SSH on port 22, the gateway UI/WebSocket on port 18789, and remote node/browser control) and shows how mis‑configuring these—especially by publishing Docker ports or enabling Tailscale Funnel—has already led to thousands of exposed instances. The core solution is to bind the gateway to 127.0.0.1 and route traffic only through a private Tailscale tailnet using the built‑in Serve mode, optionally using token‑based auth for direct tailnet binds. The guide is written as a practical, step‑by‑step tutorial aimed at developers or sysadmins deploying OpenClaw, using the metaphor of “operator surfaces” as doors that must stay closed unless deliberately opened.","totalInputTokens":10434,"totalOutputTokens":4888,"totalCacheReadTokens":4864,"totalCacheWriteTokens":0,"totalDurationMs":5522,"totalCostUsd":0.001286766,"pricingSource":"local-openrouter-estimate","telemetry":{"model":"openai/gpt-oss-120b:nitro","chunkSize":"10p","totalChunks":7,"totalInputTokens":10434,"totalOutputTokens":4888,"totalCacheReadTokens":4864,"totalCacheWriteTokens":0,"totalDurationMs":5522,"totalCostUsd":0.001286766,"pricingSource":"local-openrouter-estimate","chunks":[{"index":0,"inputTokens":1385,"outputTokens":1000,"cacheReadTokens":512,"cacheWriteTokens":0,"durationMs":1188,"costUsd":0.000234015},{"index":1,"inputTokens":1623,"outputTokens":776,"cacheReadTokens":512,"cacheWriteTokens":0,"durationMs":1243,"costUsd":0.000202977},{"index":2,"inputTokens":1425,"outputTokens":363,"cacheReadTokens":768,"cacheWriteTokens":0,"durationMs":354,"costUsd":0.000120915},{"index":3,"inputTokens":1628,"outputTokens":737,"cacheReadTokens":768,"cacheWriteTokens":0,"durationMs":595,"costUsd":0.000196152},{"index":4,"inputTokens":1533,"outputTokens":709,"cacheReadTokens":768,"cacheWriteTokens":0,"durationMs":585,"costUsd":0.000187407},{"index":5,"inputTokens":1379,"outputTokens":683,"cacheReadTokens":768,"cacheWriteTokens":0,"durationMs":682,"costUsd":0.000176721},{"index":6,"inputTokens":1461,"outputTokens":620,"cacheReadTokens":768,"cacheWriteTokens":0,"durationMs":875,"costUsd":0.000168579}]}}
{"runId":"qwen-qwen3-32b-nitro@2026-05-13T23-04-10-151Z","slug":"securing-clawdbot-tailscale","locale":"es","model":"qwen/qwen3-32b:nitro","modelPath":"qwen-qwen3-32b-nitro","createdAt":"2026-05-13T23:04:45.715Z","sourcePath":"src/content/posts/2026-01-26--securing-clawdbot-tailscale/index.mdx","targetPath":"src/content/posts/2026-01-26--securing-clawdbot-tailscale/es/index.mdx","candidatePath":"reports/i18n/securing-clawdbot-tailscale/es/qwen-qwen3-32b-nitro/2026-05-13T23-04-10-151Z/candidate.mdx","sourceHash":"774feafac3dd3c408584db2b169a365e3f58a8b6a6d0541778aad55f122f5285","outputHash":"222171d40c203ad3987219c3d82fb332e19b5cea16c1ea419ede03f4c44fae27","reasoningEffort":"low","temperature":0.3,"maxTokens":16000,"timeoutMs":200000,"articleSummary":"The article warns that misconfigured OpenClaw AI assistants—used across messaging platforms—can expose systems to shell access risks by leaving gateway interfaces, SSH, or node controls publicly accessible. It emphasizes securing deployments via Tailscale’s private network, binding gateway services to loopback, and avoiding public exposure unless explicitly required. Key technologies discussed include OpenClaw’s gateway API, Tailscale’s Serve/Funnel modes, and SSH hardening. The tone is instructional, framing security as a manageable task for non-experts through concrete setup steps. Metaphors like “operator surfaces” and “remote code execution” highlight risks, while recurring warnings about Shodan-scanned vulnerabilities and GitHub audit findings underscore urgency. Intended for developers/sysadmins deploying OpenClaw, the guide prioritizes practical, secure defaults over convenience.","totalInputTokens":9263,"totalOutputTokens":8395,"totalCacheReadTokens":2048,"totalCacheWriteTokens":0,"totalDurationMs":18873,"totalCostUsd":0.0027558399999999994,"pricingSource":"local-openrouter-estimate","telemetry":{"model":"qwen/qwen3-32b:nitro","chunkSize":"10p","totalChunks":7,"totalInputTokens":9263,"totalOutputTokens":8395,"to